<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="97" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1578,2035]" pageId="16" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,383,1578,1603]" pageId="16" pageNumber="97">Material examined</emphasis>
. Holotype male with the following labels: Pencil label handwritten with cursive writing appearing to be the following: “ror 7” Pencil label, handwritten with upper and lower case block letters: “Sven Hedins exp. [indecipherable] CenterAsien Leg. Dr. Hummel.” Printed label: “N.O. Szechuan: Ufer von Kia-ling-ho swischen Naupo Und Pao-ning-fu 
<date box="[542,656,1686,1711]" pageId="16" pageNumber="97" value="1930-05-16">16.V.1930</date>
[Hummel leg.]” Pencil label, handwritten with upper and lower case block letters: “ 
<taxonomicName authority="Forssl." authorityName="Forsslund" authorityYear="1935" box="[318,598,1722,1747]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simulans">Marilia simulans Forssl.</taxonomicName>
Typus ♂ 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[715,780,1722,1747]" pageId="16" pageNumber="97">n. sp.</emphasis>
” Printed label: “NHRS-TOBI 000000856” Printed label: “Loan 0 0 1/2016 NHRS-TOBI 000000856” This holotype specimen is missing the following body parts: Left flagellum beyond segment 3; Maxillary and labial palps; Left foreleg; Right wings; Abdominal segments VI–X. The remaining specimen has been cleared and is mostly transparent. The left wings remain, but are frayed, without setae other than the bristles on the forewing anal vein, and the dorsal and ventral cuticular layers have separated, so that parts of these wings could not be illustrated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="98" pageId="16" pageNumber="97" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1578,2035]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1437,151,536]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="98" pageId="16" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1938,1963]" pageId="16" pageNumber="97">Remarks.</emphasis>
The wing venation of this species closely resembles that of 
<taxonomicName box="[982,1119,1939,1963]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discaulis">
<emphasis box="[982,1005,1939,1962]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="97">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1019,1119,1939,1963]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="97">discaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Each hind wing has a small posterobasal lobe (not shown in 
<figureCitation box="[521,601,1974,1999]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1533,1555]" captionTargetBox="[163,1427,603,1498]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,591,1511]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 12. Marilia simulans Forsslund 1935, male genitalia, head, and wings. 12 A – 12 B, male genitalia (after Forsslund 1935): 12 A, right lateral; 12 B, ventral; 12 C, right forewing, dorsal (after Forsslund 1935). 12 E – 12 F, male head and wings (original drawings from holotype): 12 E, head, dorsal; 12 Fa – 12 Fp, left wings, ventral: 12 Fa, forewing; 12 Fp, hind wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/891604/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="97">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
Fp); any long basal brush of setae is missing, but the lobe has many setal alveoli, suggesting that the brush was present in the undamaged specimen. Also, the compound eyes are separated from each other and the intervening setal warts are poorly defined, as in 
<taxonomicName box="[959,1095,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discaulis">
<emphasis box="[959,982,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[996,1095,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">discaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The genitalia were illustrated in lateral and ventral views by 
<bibRefCitation author="Forsslund" box="[520,720,188,213]" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" refString="Forsslund, K. - H. (1935) Swedisch-chinesische wissenshaftliche Expedition nach den nordwestlichen Provinzen Chinas, unter Leitung von Dr. Sven Hedin and Prof. Su Ping-Chang. Insecten gesammelt vom schwedischen Arzt der Expedition Dr. David Hummel 1927 - 1930. 50: Trichoptera. Archiv for Zoologi, 27 A (31), 1 - 21." type="journal article" year="1935">Forsslund (1935)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forsslund" authorityYear="1935" box="[734,931,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simulans">
<emphasis box="[734,931,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">Marilia simulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[1091,1232,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discaulis">
<emphasis box="[1091,1114,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1132,1232,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">discaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following characters: (1) the lateral view of tergum X was depicted as a slender and acute structure in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forsslund" authorityYear="1935" box="[1217,1356,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simulans">
<emphasis box="[1217,1356,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">M. simulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is nearly rounded in 
<taxonomicName box="[356,492,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discaulis">
<emphasis box="[356,379,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[393,492,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">discaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[508,612,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1388,1410]" captionTargetBox="[166,1418,452,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,447,1366]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Marilia discaulis new species, male genitalia, head, and wings. 10 A – 10 D, male genitalia: 10 A, left lateral; 10 B, dorsal; 10 Bv, tergum X, ventral; 10 C, left inferior appendage (paired), ventral; 10 D, phallus, left lateral; 10 E, head, dorsal. 10 El, left antennal base, lateral. 10 Fa – 10 Fp, right wings, dorsal: 10 Fa, forewing; 10 Fp, hind wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/891600/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
); 2) the harpago of each inferior appendage is about 3 times as long as its width and is almost 1/3 as long as the coxopodite in lateral or ventral views in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forsslund" authorityYear="1935" box="[1027,1164,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simulans">
<emphasis box="[1027,1164,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">M. simulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it is only 2 times as long as its width and is not quite 1/5 as long as the coxopodite in lateral or ventral views in 
<taxonomicName box="[1166,1303,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discaulis">
<emphasis box="[1166,1303,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">M. discaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1388,1410]" captionTargetBox="[166,1418,452,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,447,1366]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Marilia discaulis new species, male genitalia, head, and wings. 10 A – 10 D, male genitalia: 10 A, left lateral; 10 B, dorsal; 10 Bv, tergum X, ventral; 10 C, left inferior appendage (paired), ventral; 10 D, phallus, left lateral; 10 E, head, dorsal. 10 El, left antennal base, lateral. 10 Fa – 10 Fp, right wings, dorsal: 10 Fa, forewing; 10 Fp, hind wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/891600/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">Figs. 10A, 10C</figureCitation>
). Despite these apparent differences, until modern specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forsslund" authorityYear="1935" box="[939,1077,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simulans">
<emphasis box="[939,962,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[977,1077,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">simulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be found, we cannot know with confidence whether 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forsslund" authorityYear="1935" box="[432,569,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simulans">
<emphasis box="[432,455,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[469,569,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">simulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[622,757,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Odontoceridae" genus="Marilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discaulis">
<emphasis box="[622,645,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[658,757,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">discaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are different species. Because of the need to be able to speak about readily identifiable species, we choose to consider them distinct species unless and until better evidence becomes available.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
